{"summary":"Accept all three amendments. The test synchronization concern and the retry-progress aggregation issue are substantive robustness/correctness problems; the clone-removal note is a valid but lower-priority cleanup.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-7-8c8af466","decision":"accept","rationale":"This is a real test robustness defect. `recv_timeout(Duration::from_millis(100))` only proves the second thread has not finished within 100 ms; it does not prove that the thread was actually scheduled and blocked on the write lock. Under load, the assertion can pass vacuously. Adding an explicit barrier or pre-lock signal from thread 2 would make the serialization claim deterministic."},{"amendment_id":"fr-7-0047ba65","decision":"accept","rationale":"This is technically correct, even if low priority. Both closures are `FnOnce`, so owned values can be moved into them and consumed directly instead of cloning `String` / `Option<String>` payloads on every call. It does not change behavior, but it removes unnecessary allocations and slightly clarifies ownership."},{"amendment_id":"fr-7-368e3c97","decision":"accept","rationale":"This is a substantive correctness issue. `reconcile_snapshot_from_lineage` computes `MilestoneProgress` by counting normalized lineage rows, but `collapse_task_run_attempts` only merges legacy start/completion pairs for the same attempt. Separate retries remain as distinct terminal rows, so one bead can be counted as both failed and completed. That conflicts with the documented meaning of the progress fields as bead counts and makes `status.json` reflect attempt history rather than current bead state."}]}